<HEAD>Undaunted By Snag, Daredevil Says He'll Brave Falls Stunt Again</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NIAGARA FALLS, Ontario (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A snag that kept a daredevil from
plunging over Niagra Falls in a barrel probably saved his life,
said the man who promised to try again after he pays the fine for
the failed illegal stunt.
   Dave Munday, who survived going over the falls in a barrel in
1985, was trying to become the first person to live through a
second descent Sunday when his foam-padded barrel got caught on a
rocky shelf about a foot from the edge.
   Munday's 650-pound barrel was left partially hanging over the
brink of the 176-foot Horseshoe Falls on the Canadian side of the
Niagara River.
   The area directly below the spot where the current took the
barrel is very rocky, the stuntman said.
   ``I've never been a religious man, but something stopped it,''
he said. ``A lot of the guys said it was fate that stopped it.
Probably I would have been dead if it went over.''
   Munday, 53, of Caistor Center, Ontario, was charged with
violating laws that prohibit river stunts. He faces a possible
$8,500 fine. Police confiscated Munday's 4-foot-by-7-foot barrel
after it was pulled out of the rapids with a crane.
   Munday said he will make another attempt to go over the falls as
soon as he pays the fine. He said he probably won't try the stunt
again this year.
   Niagara Parks Police, who patrol the Canadian side of the twin
waterfalls, said Munday's barrel was dropped into the river about
660 feet above the brink of the Horseshoe Falls about shortly
before 5 a.m. Sunday.
   Police spokesman George Bailey said Ontario Hydro had been
diverting half the river's flow overnight to power its
hydroelectric plant. That kept the river level low, helping snag
Munday's barrel on the rocky ledge, he said.
   Munday said he wanted to be nearer the center of the river,
where the volume of water is greater and provides a better cushion
against the rocks at the bottom.
   On Oct. 5, 1985, Munday became the seventh daredevil to
successfully go over the falls in a vessel. Three others who tried
before him died.
   Last month, a man who went over the falls in a kayak apparently
died. The battered kayak belonging to Jessie Sharp, of Ocoee,
Tenn., was found below the falls, but his body has not been
recovered.
   After his 1985 plunge, Munday told reporters, ``Anyone who would
go over the falls twice would have to be crazy.''
</TEXT>
