<HEAD>Gore Says Dukakis Remarks Show Foreign Policy Ignorance</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Will be topped after 9:30 a.m. EDT appearance in Washington.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NIAGRA FALLS, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Albert Gore Jr. says Michael
Dukakis lacks foreign policy experience and ``simply doesn't know
what he's talking about'' when it comes to using nuclear weapons
and American military power.
   Trying to catch up with Dukakis and Jesse Jackson before
Tuesday's important New York primary, Gore maintained Wednesday
that Dukakis had made ``a major blunder'' by discussing in a
newspaper interview when he would use nuclear weapons against the
Soviet Union.
   He stood by his criticism in the face of a strong denial by
Dukakis. The Massachusetts governor said he had merely reflected
existing American and NATO policy in holding open the option of a
nuclear response to a successful Soviet invasion of Western Europe
with conventional forces.
   The Tennesse senator offered broader criticism as well, faulting
Dukakis for advocating a ban on flight testing of ballistic
missiles and for what he said were remarks supporting the
commitment of American troops in the event of Communist invaders in
West Germany or South Korea.
   ``I think in a lot of these matters he simply doesn't know what
he's talking about, and he needs an opportunity to clarify his
remarks and I want to give him an opportuhity to do so,'' Gore said
to reporters.
   A long-distance exchange between the two candidates was touched
off by an interview with Dukakis published Wednesday in the Daily
News of New York. Gore characterized Dukakis' remarks as amounting
to saying ``he would launch a nuclear first strike against the
Soviet Union if they invaded Europe with conventional forces.''
   Dukakis, in Boston, insisted Gore was distorting his comments.
Dukakis said his position was that he would consider the use of
nuclear forces as an option in the event of a successful Soviet
invasion of Europe. ``That has been the policy of our government,''
Dukakis said. ``It is the policy of the NATO alliance.''
   In a transcript provided by the newspaper, Dukakis was asked if
he could conceive of a scenario in which he would use nuclear
weapons first, ``as a strategic weapon.'' His response began,
``Yes, yes. I would hope I wouldn't have to.'' He said he was for
``a policy of no early first use. But our present strategy in
Europe assumes that if the Soviets were to invade and conventional
forces couldn't stop them that we'd reserve the right to use
nuclear force.''
   James Steinberg, the defense and foreign policy adviser to
Dukakis, said Dukakis started answering the question thinking he
was being asked about tactical nuclear weapons. The reference to
``strategic'' was made after Dukakis had started speaking,
Steinberg said.
   Steinberg said he assumed Dukakis would have given a different
answer had he understood the question to be about strategic nuclear
weapons.
   Gore campaign manager Fred Martin insisted Gore had not
distorted Dukakis' words. Both Gore and Martin said Dukakis had
erred in getting into a discussion of nuclear first use.
   ``I think it is most unwise for a president of the United States
or a major candidate for the presidency to be drawn into a
hypothetical discussion of when we would launch our nuclear forces
and trigger destruction of human civilization,'' Gore said. ``To
specify in advance when we would make that fateful step is most
unwise and irresponsible.''
   Appearing later before Westchester County Democrats in Rye
Brook, N.Y., Gore stressed that Dukakis had been asked about
``strategic'' nuclear weapons.
   ``NATO has purposely refused to respond to that hypothetical,''
Gore said. ``The president of the United States has traditionally
refused to respond to that hypothetical.''
   Gore's criticism and the ensuing flap overshadowed an event
Wednesday when Gore went to the Love Canal toxic waste site at
Niagra Falls to underscore his commitment to environmental
protection and blast the Reagan administration.
   As a congressman, Gore chaired congressional hearings that
looked into the dumping of toxic wastes at the site.
</TEXT>
</DOC>

