<HL> )HL    Heard on the Street:
Niagara Mohawk Power's Prospects Seem Dim
To Some Because of Its Stake in Nuclear Plant
---
By Bill Paul</HL>
<DD> 08/17/87</DD>
<SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO>
<IN> NMK RGS CNH NGE
HEARD ON THE STREET (HRD)
STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)
NUCLEAR POWER, FUEL (NUK)
UTILITIES (UTI) </IN>
<TEXT>
   Few companies have put their shareholders through the wringer as much as Niagara Mohawk Power has recently.

   Last month, the Syracuse, N.Y.-based utility slashed its dividend 42%, to $1.20 a share annually, and took a $755 million write-off of nuclear-plant costs that regulators won't let it charge ratepayers.
Then the utility reported a $569.4 million loss for the first half, compared with profit of $238.3 million a year earlier.

   Niagara Mohawk's stock price has rebounded a bit in the market's latest surge, with some investors believing that all the bad news is finally out and the utility is on the road to financial recovery.
However, some analysts warn that things could get even worse.

   "It isn't like the uncertainty (surrounding Niagara Mohawk) has moved into the background," says Robin M. Jaffe, a utility analyst at Dean Witter Reynolds Inc.

   Niagara Mohawk's major problem remains the Nine Mile Point 2 nuclear power plant.
Niagara Mohawk has a 41% stake in the plant, which is completed and licensed but not yet in commercial operation.
Meanwhile, the New York Public Service Commission has put a $4.16 billion cap on how much of the plant's costs can be passed on to ratepayers by Niagara Mohawk and the plant's four other utility owners.
The write-off Niagara Mohawk took last month fully reflects the utility's financial damage from that cap agreement if the plant goes into commercial operation in January, as the company expects.

   That is a big if, says James K. Asselstine, a utility bond analyst at Donaldson, Lufkin &amp; Jenrette Inc. Mr. Asselstine, who recently came to Wall Street after serving on the Nuclear Regulatory Commission, doubts that Nine Mile 2 will have a smooth start-up, given the problems the utility has had testing the plant's hardware, especially certain safety-critical valves.

   "It took (Niagara Mohawk) a long time to deal with those (hardware) problems," says Mr. Asselstine, who also is worried by the "deteriorating" operating performance of Niagara Mohawk at its Nine Mile Point 1 unit.

   Judith Warrick, a utility analyst at Morgan Stanley &amp; Co. says that if Nine Mile 2 encounters a lengthy delay beyond January, Niagara Mohawk may be forced to cut its dividend yet again.
The stock would be "fairly valued" at 13 1/2 to 14 a share, compared with its current price of 15 1/4, she says.

   Ms. Warrick also has concerns about Rochester Gas &amp; Electric and Central Hudson Gas &amp; Electric, which have a 14% and a 9% stake in Nine Mile 2, respectively.
She believes there is a "fairly high possibility" both will have to trim dividends because of Nine Mile 2 costs.

   New York State Electric &amp; Gas, which has an 18% stake, also may have to trim dividends if it doesn't get the public service commission to approve its request for a 13% return on equity, Ms. Warrick says.

   Without Nine Mile 2, Niagara Mohawk would be a solid investment, analysts say.
While the utility's service territory in New York state isn't likely to experience much industrial growth in the next few years, Niagra Mohawk's power-production costs are reasonable, largely because of low-cost hydropower and nuclear power from Nine Mile 1.
And, like other utilities seeking new sources of revenue, Niagara Mohawk recently amended its charter to allow it to go into non-utility businesses.
However, it hasn't announced any specific plans to do so.

   Paul L. Gioia, a senior vice president at First Albany Corp. and a former chairman of the public service commission, recently issued a buy recommendation.
While he acknowledged some "lingering risk" because of Nine Mile 2, Mr. Gioia said Niagara Mohawk's financial condition "should consistently improve over the next several years."

   However, Daniel Scotto, a utility bond analyst at L.F. Rothschild, Unterberg, Towbin Inc. sees other clouds on Niagara Mohawk's horizon.
Mr. Scotto thinks the current head of the commission, Peter Bradford, will push for statewide pooling of generating plants of all New York utilities.
Such a pooling, which would effectively place electricity distribution under state control, would presumably better match up supply with demand at the lowest possible price, resulting in significant savings for some ratepayers.

   Mr. Scotto says such an agreement also would mean that the relatively high-cost power from Nine Mile 2 probably would be sold at discount in the bulk-power market.
That would hurt all of Nine Mile 2's owners financially, Mr. Scotto says -- although he quickly adds that Mr. Bradford hasn't yet given any indication that he intends to push for such a pooling agreement.

