<HEAD>Bush And Mulroney Take In The Blue Jays' Opener</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 8th graf: ``Spotting a,'' with Bush comment on ladies
in the locker room</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush and Prime Minister Brian Mulroney
together tossed out the first balls Tuesday to begin the Toronto
Blue Jays' opening game against Bush's homestate Texas Rangers.
   The two smiled broadly as they threw the balls to a group of
ballplayers standing under the covered Skydome.
   Boos were mixed with applause as Bush and Mulroney came onto the
field and a huge banner reading ``Axe the Tax'' was plastered
across the bleachers. Mulroney's proposed 7 percent tax on goods
and services, passed Tuesday by the House of Commons, is widely
unpopular.
   Bush and Mulroney wore matching royal blue baseball jackets _
Mulroney's emblazoned with the Blue Jays' logo and Bush's with the
name of the Texas team partly owned by his son, George W. Bush.
   They later shed the jackets for their suit-and-tie outfits as
they sat in an upper-level VIP box overlooking the field. Bush, a
baseball fan and former captain of his Yale University team, ate
snacks as they watched the game.
   Before the game, Bush and Mulroney visited the locker rooms of
each team. In the Rangers' dressing room, Bush said he was cheering
for his son's team.
   ``Got to raise the flag,'' he said. Bush's adoptive home state
is Texas.
   Spotting a woman photographer in the Rangers' locker room, Bush
exclaimed: ``Ladies in the locker room! A new era!''
   The Blue Jays, the defending American League East champions,
drew a near-sellout crowd to the 51,000-seat stadium.
   The stadium officials provided visiting reporters with
``skyfacts'' about the venue Bush's entourage was visiting.
   Among them:
   _Eight miles of zippers hold down the baseball field's bright
green turf.
   _The facility's 1,280 toilets, if flushed simultaneously, would
use the amount of water that flows over Niagra Falls in three
seconds.
   _The amount of toilet paper used in its first year of operation
could reach to the moon.
</TEXT>
