<HEAD>Border Merchants Float On Tide Of Canadian Money</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: All dollars are U.S.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BF1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FLIPPEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NIAGARA FALLS, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Merchants along the country's
northern border are floating on a tide of Canadian dollars,
watching sales figures swell at a time when shopping elsewhere in
the United States is slumping.
   Canadians have been traveling by car and bus from as far as 100
miles away this year to snap up goods that sell in the United
States for as low as half their cost back home.
   As a result, stores all along the border that reported record
sales last year - when retailing nationwide was stagnant - say
business is even better this Christmas.
   Bob Bowen, merchandising manager of a Kmart Corp. store outside
Niagara Falls, N.Y., said sales were up 15 percent over last year.
``And last year was a banner year, too,'' he said.
   Down the road, stores at the Factory Outlet Mall have been
reporting sales increases of anywhere from 5 percent to more than
10 percent over last year, said Pat Doyle, the mall's marketing
manager. She said up to 90 percent of the mall's customers are
Canadian.
   Parking lots at the Kmart and the mall were filled Wednesday
with cars bearing Ontario license plates, and chartered buses from
Canada were parked at the front.
   But seven miles away, at a Kmart in Niagara Falls, Ontario, only
three cashiers were on duty and the store was noticeably quiet.
   ``You Buffalo people are killing us,'' said merchandising
manager Dan Gimpel. ``There's not a heck of a lot we can do. People
are convinced there's bargains over there and they go over.''
   Richard Delisle, assistant district manager of Canada Customs in
Niagara Falls, Ontario, said the number of people paying duties on
goods purchased in the United States between April and October, the
most recent figures available, jumped 75 percent from last year's
record high.
   ``Each year we're looking at increases to unprecedented
levels,'' Delisle said.
   The story is the same in border towns across the country. In
Bellingham, Wash., 45 miles south of Vancouver, business at the
Bellis Fair Mall is up slightly thanks to the Canadians, said
marketing director Wendy Ripley.
   ``People are always amazed to see our parking lot and all the
Canadian cars in it,'' she said.
   In northern New York, motels are full of shoppers from as far
away as Ottawa and Montreal, and three-hour delays have been
reported on the international bridges.
   A recent study estimated that Sault Ste. Marie, Ontario,
businesses lose $140 million a year in sales to stores in much
smaller Sault Ste. Marie, Mich. The study, by Ernst &amp; Young in
Toronto, estimated the loss nationwide at $2 billion.
   Shopping by Canadians has surged even though Canada officially
is in a recession. Bern Rotman, spokesman for the New York State
Department of Economic Development, said the hard times in Canada
might actually spur more cross-border shopping.
   ``As the expendible income gets smaller in Canada - if that's
the case - it may very well be that the bargain that's had in the
United States is even more a siren song,'' he said.
   The price differences on many everyday items are staggering. An
eight-pack of batteries, for example, costs $3.97 in the United
States but $6.85 in Canada. A roll of color slide film that would
be less than $10 in New York is $14.59 in Ontario. Canadians pay
the equivalent of $2.16 a gallon for self-serve unleaded gas, while
those in Buffalo pay $1.43.
   ``A Canadian Kmart could probably come over here and buy power
tools cheaper off my counter than they could from their distributor
in Canada,'' said Thomas Reddy, general manager of the Niagara
Falls, N.Y., Kmart.
   Pam Clarkin said she drives 65 miles round-trip from her home in
Grassie, Ontario, to do her weekly grocery shopping in Niagara
Falls.
   ``Usually at home I pay about $120'' for a week's worth of
groceries, Clarkin said. ``Here I can get it for about $70.''
   Brian Kellett, a 19-year-old student at the University of
Toronto, said his fellow students make the 90-mile drive to Niagara
Falls as often as every two weeks to stock up on cheap booze and
cigarettes.
   ``Everybody comes down, they buy like a big jug of schnapps or
something,'' he said.
   Last year, Niagara Falls, N.Y., residents grumbled about the
traffic and litter problems they blamed on the Canadians. Merchants
said they had heard fewer complaints this year and speculated that
American shoppers have simply learned to put up with the crowds.
   ``They stay off the roads or go to Amherst (15 miles south)
where it's not so bad,'' said Bill Hench, manager of a Wallet Works
store at the outlet mall.
</TEXT>
