<HEAD>U.S. May Allow Stranded Family To Return</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Cuban family from Florida stranded in
Canada since a pre-Christmas sightseeing trip because of
immigration problems reportedly may soon be allowed to return home.
   Immigration and Naturalization Service District Director
Benedict J. Ferro will approve Carlos Fajardo's bid for political
asylum within the next few weeks, ending the family's exile in Fort
Erie, Ontario, The Buffalo News reported today.
   Fajardo, his wife, Bermaida Zamora-Powers, and her two children
have lived on charity since Dec. 23, when they were denied re-entry
into the United States at the Rainbow Bridge in Niagara Falls.
   The couple, both considered illegal aliens, told border
authorities that they had driven north to see snow for Christmas
and had crossed the border into Canada to view Niagara Falls.
   Fajardo owns a home and a small boat-building business in Miami.
Officials have alleged he entered the United States illegally in
1985 from Panama. His wife and her children by a previous marriage
allegedly entered the country illegally in 1986 from Venezuela and
an immigration judge ordered them deported last August.
   Ferro would not discuss the case in detail but confirmed that
new information could substantiate Fajardo's claims that he would
face political persecution if he were returned to his native Cuba.
   ``Mr. Fajardo's claim is clearly not frivolous,'' Ferro said
told the News. ``If indeed it proves to rise to the level of a
well-founded fear of being persecuted if returned to Cuba, we will
grant him asylum.''
   ``It looks like we may be able to work something out,'' said
Sister Kathleen Rimar, Fajardo's Catholic Charities attorney in
Buffalo.
   After they were denied re-entry, the Fajardos lived for several
weeks in a motel in Niagara Falls, Ontario, then in a Fort Erie
apartment under the sponsorship of Ontario refugee groups.
   Fajardo had a previous application for asylum pending, but it
was nullified when he crossed the border into Canada, officials
said.
</TEXT>
