<HEAD>Four Cling To Rocks Above Horseshoe Falls Before Rescue</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NIAGARA FALLS, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Workers formed a human chain and
waded into the Niagara River rapids to rescue four people who clung
to rocks 40 feet above the falls for about an hour after their boat
capsized, authorities said.
   The four began drinking on the 26-foot boat Wednesday evening at
a marina in Chippawa, Ontario, and were unaware they had drifted so
close to Horseshoe Falls, the celebrated 158-foot drop on the
Canadian side of the border, authorities said.
   No one was steering, said Sgt. James Dugos of the Niagara
Regional State Parks Police. ``I'm very much surprised that all
four people were saved,'' he said.
   The four abandoned the boat when it capsized 40 yards from the
brink of the falls and were rescued early Thursday, suffering only
bumps and scrapes. The $130,000 boat was swept over the falls and
destroyed.
   David Shand, 34, said he thought he and his companions would die
as they clasped the rocks with the roar of the falls in their ears.
   ``You had to be out there,'' said the owner of the boat, David
Mason, 35. ``It's like something you dream about in the middle of
the night.''
   A camper in Goat Island State Park heard the four screaming and
called for help.
   Warning signs and the rapids of the upper Niagara River usually
discourage boaters from getting too close to the falls.
   No charges have been filed against the four, all residents of
Niagara Falls, Ontario.
</TEXT>
</DOC>

