<HEAD>Canadian Borders Reopen to Trucking as Independents Lift Blockade</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: also on general news wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOSE MARTINEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WINDSOR, Ontario (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Truck traffic resumed across the
Canadian-U.S. border after Canada's transport minister persuaded
drivers to end their blockade, and automakers began reopening
plants shut by parts shortages.
   Chrysler Corp. recalled 3,200 workers to its Windsor minivan
plant today after independent Canadian truckers lifted a blockade
of the Ambassador Bridge, a major supply route for U.S.-made auto
parts.
   ``The situation is looking better by the hour,'' said Chrysler
Canada spokesman Walter McCall. ``The flow of materials has been
restored and the likelihood is good that workers will be on their
full shifts (today).''
   But truckers at some other southern Ontario border points,
including Fort Erie across the Niagara River from Buffalo, N.Y.,
and Niagara Falls, remained snarled late Thursday.
   Trucks still were blocking a lane of the Lewiston-Queenston
Bridge at Niagara Falls, allowing only cars to pass, state police
said.
   Trucks were not being allowed across the Peace Bridge linking
Buffalo and Fort Erie, and about 100 to 200 trucks were parked on
each side of the span, bridge officials said.
   In Windsor, the blockade of 300 trucks strangled traffic
Wednesday and part of Thursday on the span between Windsor and
Detroit but gave way to a steady stream of trucks moving in a
single lane by Thursday evening.
   The work stoppage was lifted after Canadian Transport Minister
Doug Lewis said he would take up with the Cabinet the truckers'
complaints about taxes and the free-trade agreement with the United
States.
   ``I am pleased to have had the opportunity to learn directly
from them their concerns about what they consider to be an unlevel
playing field,'' he said.
   Lewis met Thursday morning in Windsor with a delegation led by
Wayne Whitney, a protest organizer, and Bill Wrye, Ontario minister
of transportation.
   About 5 p.m. Thursday, the crowd of protesters dispersed,
apparently pleased with the agreement, said Windsor police Staff
Sgt. R. Nichols.
   ``There were about 200 people and another 100 to 150 trucks
there. But the truckers were happy, got into their trucks and drove
away,'' Nichols said.
   A sign thanking U.S. truckers for their support during the
blockade hung at an intersection where truckers had congregated
during the strike.
   The protest was sparked by proposed increases in Canada's Goods
and Services Tax that will affect the goods that truckers haul as
well as the tires, insurance and diesel fuel they buy.
   The U.S.-Canadian trade agreement, which will remove almost all
tariffs by 1999, will further handicap Canadian truckers,
protesters said.
   The truckers said taxes and the free-trade agreement are
crippling their ability to compete with U.S. drivers.
   The blockade also forced the shutdown of three General Motors of
Canada Ltd. plants in Ontario and production cutbacks at one in
Quebec. Some 13,000 auto workers were affected. Production also was
disrupted at Ford of Canada.
   Ford plants closed early Thursday in Dearborn and Wayne, Mich.;
Lorain and Avon, Ohio; Louisville; and Minneapolis, said company
spokesman Peter Olsen.
   At Mazda Motor Corp.'s plant in Flat Rock, Mich., 20 miles south
of Detroit, workers went home early Wednesday and Thursday, said
spokesman Tom McDonald.
   Protesters also had blocked the truck lanes at the Canadian end
of the Blue Water Bridge between Sarnia and Port Huron, Mich.,
while in Sault Ste. Marie, supervisor Jim Blain at the
International Bridge said he received conflicting reports about the
work stoppage.
   At Fort Erie, about 200 trucks jammed the approaches to the
international Peace Bridge to Buffalo, N.Y. At Blackpool, Quebec,
just across the border from Champlain, N.Y., a heavily armed squad
of police persuaded Quebec truckers to dismantle their blockade
Thursday morning.
   No violence was reported at any of the blockaded border points.
</TEXT>
</DOC>

