<HEAD>High Taxes Drive Canadian Beer Buyers Across The Border</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: All dollar figures are U.S.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FLIPPEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FORT ERIE, Ontario (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Visitors to this border town shouldn't
be surprised if the cold Canadian beer their host offers them has
an ``imported'' stamp on it these days.
   An increasing number of Canadians who live near the U.S. border
have taken to buying their favorite brews in the United States,
where popular Canadian beers sell for as little as half the price
charged back home.
   The trend is seriously worrying the managers of beer outlets in
border towns such as Fort Erie, just across the Niagara River from
Buffalo, N.Y. They say they're hamstrung because of government
controls on price and marketing.
   ``We're not on a level playing field,'' said Gordon Reichett,
manager of the Fort Erie Beer Store. ``There's no way for us to do
anything about the marketing because we're limited by the (Ontario)
Liquor Control Board.''
   In Ontario, for example, beer may be sold only through Beer
Store outlets and provincial liquor stores, and prices, by law,
must be the same everywhere.
   That leaves border-area beer sellers unable to meet the
competition from New York supermarkets, which use beer as a loss
leader to lure customers.
   ``We use some beers ... as draws to get people into the
stores,'' said Mark Zee, manager of a Tops supermarket in Buffalo.
``We don't lose money on it but we don't make a lot either.''
   In Buffalo, Canadian brands such as Molson Golden or Labatt's
Blue cost about $12 a case, including tax, deposit and the
round-trip toll on the international Peace Bridge. The same beer
costs $19.65 a case at Beer Store outlets, which control 94 percent
of Ontario's beer trade.
   The price difference has existed for years, but merchants on
both sides of the border said Canadians only began shopping for
beer in the United States in large numbers about a year ago, when
the Canadian dollar strengthened against U.S. dollar and American
stores began advertising heavily in Canada.
   Reichett said business at his store is off 11 percent from last
year's pace.
   Sales would be even slower if it weren't for U.S. shoppers
seeking premium high-alcohol Canadian beers that are unavailable in
the United States. Those buyers now make up almost 25 percent of
his business, he says.
   ``The Fort Erie people are not buying the Molson Dry and the
Brador and the Extra Stock ales,'' Reichett said. ``It's the
American clientele, and thank God for them.''
   Canada Customs does not keep statistics on beer imports, but
inspectors at the Peace Bridge estimate that Canadian brands
account for about 30 percent of the beer that Canadians bring back
from the United States.
   Jan Westcott, executive director of the trade group Brewers of
Ontario, said the problem exists throughout the province's borders
with New York, Michigan and Minnesota. He said high alcohol taxes
are the culprit.
   ``If you take $10 worth of tax off and account a little for the
exchange rate, there's not that much difference in the price,'' he
said. ``We have a very aggressive tax policy with respect to
alcohol.''
   Even when you add in $6.80 a case in tax and duty collected by
Canada Customs at the border, it's cheaper to buy beer in New York.
And that's only if shoppers declare their beer. Some don't, and
many who do say they often are waved through without paying duty.
   ``They're pretty slack on the bridges these days, letting people
go back and forth with whatever they want,'' said Larry Shale,
manager of the Beer Store in Niagara Falls, He said business at his
store is off almost 20 percent in the past year.
   ``If they were stricter in controlling what goes over the
bridges, that would help us.''
   Customs officials say that's an exaggeration, but admit many
shoppers do get by without paying duty, especially on busy days.
   ``We get some days where the traffic's backed up across the
bridge,'' Stuart McLeod, a Canada Customs supervisor in Fort Erie.
``There's no way of collecting duty on every single case.''
</TEXT>
