<HEAD>Up to Foot of Snow in Colorado, Roads Icy in Nebraska, New England
Wet</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 9 grafs to update with snow amounts in Wyoming and
Nebraska, picking up 9th graf pvs, ``It's snowing ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROGER PETTERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   An Election Day storm dumped heavy snow on the Rockies and left
highways slippery on the western Plains, and snow over the Great
Lakes closed some Michigan schools.
   ``In some counties we've had trouble even getting poll workers
to the polls to open them up,'' said Nebraska Secretary of State
Allen Beermann.
   High wind knocked out power to thousands of customers in upstate
New York, and heavy rain soaked parts of New England.
   Heavy snow fell across parts of Wyoming from late Monday into
Tuesday. Snowfall totals ranged up to 17 inches at Sinks Canyon, 7
miles southwest of Lander; 13 inches at Lander; 12 inches at
Togwotee Pass, 40 miles northeast of Jackson; and up to a foot at
Casper. Casper Mountain got nearly 3 feet of snow in a 30-hour
period, the National Weather Service said.
   In Colorado, the National Weather Service said snow increased in
coverage and intensity in Denver and other Front Range areas during
the morning rush hour. The snow was driven by wind blowing at 15 to
25 mph, cutting visibility.
