<HEAD>Don't Give Up Perry's Flagship</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Launch scheduled Saturday, Sept. 10</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto PG1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER MATTIACE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ERIE, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Commodore Oliver Hazard Perry: They didn't give
up your ship.
   The brigantine Niagara, restored to fighting trim and still
flying Perry's battle flag, ``Don't Give Up the Ship,'' is
scheduled to be returned to the Great Lakes on Saturday, exactly
175 years after Perry's fleet defeated the British in the Battle of
Lake Erie.
   ``Perry would recognize his old ship. This is as exact a
restoration as there can be,'' said Melbourne Smith, an Annapolis,
Md., marine architect who dismantled the Niagara and rebuilt it to
historical specifications.
   The 182-foot, 278-ton ship, restored for the third time with
$3.8 million in state and private money in dry dock at this port
city, will be outfitted by next spring with 118-foot and 113-foot
masts, square rigging, about 22,000 square feet of polyester sail
and 20 aluminum cannons.
   Then, it is to tour the Great Lakes and East Coast ports as
Pennsylvania's ``official flagship.''
   The first USS Niagara was one of six small ships built at Erie
during the War of 1812 and put under Perry's command to break a
British blockade of American Great Lakes ports and to defend the
Northwest Territory.
   On Sept. 10, 1813, Perry's nine-ship squadron met six British
vessels under Commodore Robert Heriot Barclay in a short but fierce
battle near Put-in-Bay, Ohio, that left 135 British and 123
American casualties.
   Perry's flagship, the USS Lawrence, was disabled by British fire
and Perry transferred to the Niagara, where he hoisted his famous
blue-and-white battle flag and attacked again. The Niagara helped
break the British battle line and forced Barclay to surrender.
   ``We have met the enemy and they are ours: two ships, two brigs,
one schooner and one sloop,'' Perry reported to his superiors.
   The Niagara served as a station ship in Erie until 1820, when
she was scuttled in nearby Misery Bay. The ship was raised by Erie
citizens in 1913 and restored for a Great Lakes tour to celebrate
the 100th anniversary of Perry's victory. She was restored again in
the 1930s and 1940s.
   The latest Niagara incorporates 42 pieces of the original ship,
some within view for visitors. Smith said the original wood is aged
and not strong enough for structural use.
   ``It will be obvious,'' he said.
   In 1813, a gang of about 300 shipwrights, blacksmiths and other
craftsmen and laborers, directed by New York shipbuilders Adam and
Noah Brown, hired on at Erie and built Perry's fleet in three
months. There were no sawmills in Erie, which then had only 500
inhabitants, and craftsmen cut, hewed and squared the unseasoned
wood by hand.
   ``It was all green wood from around here. It wouldn't last two
years,'' Smith said. ``But it didn't matter. This was a throwaway
boat for war.''
   Smith's modern crew of about 60, working over 99 days, included
shipwrights and carpenters experienced in restoring old ships. They
were assisted by laborers from the Pennsylvania Conservation Corps,
a job training program for disadvantaged youth.
   They worked in a dockyard where Perry's smaller gunboats were
built in 1813. The Niagara and Lawrence were built nearby,
according to project spokeswoman Maura McLaughlin.
   The Niagara's new 18-pound carronades, which are stubby cannons
for short-range use, and two 12-pound long guns, will be cast at an
Erie foundry of aluminum to save 10 tons of weight on deck. The
Navy removed the original cannons before sinking the Niagara.
   ``Ships like this weren't very safe to sail. They were top
heavy,'' Smith said. ``But it was wartime and it didn't matter. In
wartime, you do dangerous things.''
   Smith estimated a crew of about 35 will be needed to sail the
restored ship as it tours the Great Lakes beginning next summer.
The state does not plan to give rides or to rent the ship.
</TEXT>
