<TEXT>
   The charge carries a maximum of five years in prison and a
$250,000 fine. But under federal sentencing guidelines, Ms. Cheng
would probably face no more than 14 months in prison when she is
sentenced Aug. 8.
   The U.S. Immigration and Naturalization Service, in a report
last July, named Ms. Cheng, 41, a resident alien who lives in New
York City, as a leader of a ring that charged would-be immigrants
$23,000 apiece to be smuggled into the United States.
   However, the indictment only charged her with the 1989 incident,
which was uncovered during a covert investigation by the INS and
the Royal Canadian Mounted Police of traffic in illegal aliens
between Toronto and New York City.
   Her clients, according to court papers, included Li Jin Mu and
his wife, Wang Sai Zhen, the refugees whose plight became a test
case for the new U.S. policy allowing fear of forced abortions to
be grounds for political asylum.
   The papers state that Ms. Cheng personally met Li, his wife and
nephew at the Toronto airport last March and paid a driver $340 to
take them to the U.S. border at Queenston, Ontario. There, a second
driver took over, driving them across the border and across New
York state to Albany.
   In Albany, another member of the ring paid the driver $3,000 and
bought the Li family bus tickets to New York City. But the drivers
were undercover agents from the Royal Canadian Mounted Police and
the INS and all involved were arrested.
   Months later, after Li and his nephew had been deported and had
been caught in another smuggling attempt _ this time jammed in with
Uruguayan refugees in the back of a tractor-trailer _ the
government granted Li and his wife political asylum.
   For other aliens, the consequences have been tragic.
   Ms. Cheng's husband, Yick Tak Cheung, is charged with smuggling
dozens of aliens in small rubber rafts across the rapids below
Niagara Falls. Some of the rafts were equipped with cellular phones
that the aliens, or their couriers, could use to arrange for
drivers to meet them on the U.S. shore.
   But they apparently were not equipped with life jackets and four
aliens drowned when a raft deflated and sank in the ice-choked
river in late December 1988.
   ``That was particularly cruel and callous on the part of the
smugglers,'' Ingham says. ``We perceive many of these aliens as
victims.''
   Court papers filed in Yick's case said his ring recruited two
Lewiston taxi drivers to drive the aliens to New York City, without
at first telling them who their fares were. When the cab drivers
figured out what was going on, the threats began.
   In a sworn statement, cab driver James Dullan said an alleged
associate of Yick's told him, ``We take care of our own, one way or
the other.''
   ``I took it as a verbal threat,'' Dullan said. ``Work with him
or else.''
   Yick has pleaded innocent. His lawyer declined to comment.
   Aliens who cannot scrape together large sums of cash can still
use the smugglers' services. To pay their debts to the smugglers,
some pledge themselves to years of menial work in restaurants.
Others allow themselves to be recruited into Chinese organized
crime groups.
   ``It's a form of indentured servitude,'' says Dennis Peruzzini,
an INS investigator in Buffalo.
   While Chinese people comprise the single biggest nationality
involved, the border patrol has caught a veritable United Nations
of aliens in the past few years.
   Large numbers of Jamaicans and Guyanese attempted to sneak into
the United States until Canada toughened its visa requirements for
residents of those Caribbean countries. Agents on the New
York-Quebec border recently found a large group of immigrants from
India, apparently dumped there by a truck driver who panicked after
hearing about a state police truck check on the radio, Ingham said.
   Thirteen were found in a 4-foot-deep, 8-foot-wide hiding space
in a truck trailer at Lewiston in May.
   A smuggling operator arrested a few years ago brought Brazilians
into the country by leading them across the Niagara rapids on the
underside of a railroad bridge, Ingham says.
   ``He'd take the group from Toronto to Niagara Falls, Ontario, by
bus and then under cover of night, he'd take them down over the
side of the bridge and climb onto the arches,'' Ingham says. ``If
you have any degree of fear of heights, that is a scary place.''
</TEXT>
