to 12, sted 10, and number of survivors as nine, sted seven; ADDS 4
grafs to UPDATE detail.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NIAGARA FALLS, Ontario (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who paddled a kayak over
Niagara Falls in a stunt was still missing this morning and parks
police resumed their search.
   The red kayak of Jessie W. Sharp, 28, of Ocoee, Tenn., was
recovered Tuesday afternoon below Horseshoe Falls on the Canadian
side. The kayak was ``all in one piece ... in fairly good condition,
all things considered,'' said Maureen Quinn, a constable with the
Niagara Parks Police.
   ``Our regular patrol is watching the river,'' Sgt. Jim Dugos said
this morning. He said police can't dive there to look for a body.
   Asked if the man were presumed dead, he said: ``You never know.
Sometimes these people turn up.''
   Ken Kitchen was working in a tower overlooking the Niagara river
when he saw Sharp in his kayak. Trying to stop him, the utility
closed the dam gates, reducing the water flow to the falls, Kitchen
said.
   The man's boat grounded, but he picked it up and moved it into
the middle of the water.
   ``We did what we could to try and stop him, but there wasn't much
time,'' Kitchen said. ``He was gone before our help could get there.
All we could do was sit and watch helplessly.''
   The Canadian falls are 181 feet high, or about as tall as a
13-story building.
   Sharp, who was last seen at about 1:45 p.m., was trying to
complete a stunt that had been planned for about 10 years, said
constable Kim Davis. Police said nobody before had ever tried to
kayak over the falls.
   ``Barrels, yes,'' Quinn said of other attempts to go safely over
the falls in enclosed capsules. But, she said, ``it doesn't seem
plausible he could do it (and survive).''
   Since 1901, at least 12 people have gone over the falls in
barrels or rubber balls; nine have survived.
   ``It's beyond me why anyone would attempt this,'' said George
Bailey of the Niagara Parks Commission. ``He obviously doesn't know
our falls.''
   Bailey said the man was accompanied by a film crew and a friend
who took photographs.
   ``He had all the confidence in the world, according to his
friend,'' Bailey said.
   During a press conference Tuesday, police showed a videotape of
the kayaker shot by a tourist. The tape shows a man in a boat
emblazoned with ``Rapidman'' on one side successfully negotiating
the rapids of the Niagara River just before the falls. Then, he
disappears.
</TEXT>
</DOC>

