<HEAD>Perry's Flagship Launched 175 Years After His Victory</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ERIE, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Commodore Oliver Hazard Perry's brigantine
Niagara was lowered slowly into the waters of Presque Isle Bay with
a new mission _ ``official flagship'' for Pennsylvania.
   The launching of the restored ship Saturday came 175 years to
the day after Perry's fleet defeated the British in the Battle of
Lake Erie and issued the famous War of 1812 dispatch, ``We have met
the enemy and they are ours.''
   ``We are starting a new page in Pennsylvania's history, and you
all are a part of it,'' Gov. Robert Casey told several thousand
people gathered for the launching ceremony.
   Casey's wife, Ellen, lifted a bottle of Erie County wine and
struck the 182-foot, 278-ton restored ship, bedecked with the
American flag and Perry's battle flag, ``Don't Give Up the Ship.''
   Brent Glass, executive director of the Pennsylvania Historical
and Museum Commission, said the weekend festivities went smoothly
overall.
   ``We admire today a great hero, Oliver Hazard Perry,'' Glass
told a crowd during the launching ceremony. ``But also remember
those men invisible to history _ the 155 men who served on the
Niagara.''
   Casey called the Niagara ``the cornerstone of new development
projects already planned at Erie's bayfront.'' The ship was
restored for the fourth time with $3.8 million in state and private
funds.
   The Niagara will be outfitted by next spring with 118-foot and
113-foot masts, square rigging, about 22,000 square feet of
polyester sail and 20 aluminum cannon.
   It will then tour the Great Lakes and East Coast ports as
Pennsylvania's flagship.
</TEXT>
</DOC>

