<HEAD>Immigration Officials Block Cuban Family's Return</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DARREN DOPP</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Cuban family stranded in Canada by
immigration problems since December will not be allowed to return
to their home in Miami while their application for asylum is
pending, federal officials said Thursday.
   Benedict Ferro, district director of the U.S. Immigration and
Naturalization Service, said he has denied a bid for humanitarian
parole for Carlos Fajardo, his wife, Bermaida Zamora-Powers, and
her two children, Yoradlys Diaz and Yoandys Diaz.
   The decision was the result of new information immigration
officials uncovered about the family, Ferro said. ``In this case,
the negative aspects (of granting a parole) far outweighed the
evidence on their behalf,'' he said.
   Ferro would not elaboratem, but said the decision was separate
from the family's asylum claim, which will be decided in a few
weeks.
   The family have been stranded in Ontario since Dec. 23, when
they crossed into Niagara Falls to view the Canadian falls and were
denied permission to return to the United States because of what
officials said is a history of immigration fraud.
   Their plight has drawn national attention, with Hispanic groups
and Florida lawmakers appealing to INS officials for their return.
   Although they were illegal aliens, they lived for several years
in Miami, where they owned a home and boat-building business and
were active in community affairs.
   Last month, Fajardo sought a special dispensation to return to
the United States while the application for political asylum was
being considered. The process takes several months and Fajardo said
he wanted his children to return to school and that he needed to
tend to his business.
   The family lives in Fort Erie, Ontario, under the care of
refugee assistance groups.
   ``They've been holding out hope that the decision would be
positive,'' said Sister Margaret Quinn of the Niagara Inter-Church
Refugee Committee. ``They've been going on that strength. Now this
will be a real disappointment.''
   Sister Margaret said the children have been attending school but
have language problems. She said Fajardo and his wife, who are
prevented from working in Canada, were bored.
   Fajardo said Thursday he was unsure of why INS officials had
denied the parole and that he was hoping his lawyer could explain
the decision.
</TEXT>
</DOC>

